Small account problems?  PDT in your way?

- trade offshore.  PDT doesn't affect offshore accts.  CMEG may be a good start.

- trade futures.  PDT doesn't exist in futures markets.  Look into Tradeovate.  You can trade mes contracts for as low as $55 per contract ($550 for /ES, /NQ, /YM). 

- use a prop firm.  APEX may be worth looking into (see my most recent YouTube videos).  Other firms, such as Frontier, are available for equities.

- trade options in a CASH account. PDT doesn't apply to CASH accts. Options settle NEXT day.  So you can take as many trades per day as you can afford, then recycle your capital for trading the next day (I have a fee videos talking about this).

- trade in more than one acct.  Buy/short what you want to trade, then do the opposite in the other acct when you want out of the trade (most brokers require $2k to short, so keep this in mind).

Trying to form a white candle üïØ today to confirm the bounce play is in progress >> 

Definition

This pattern is characterized by a large white body engulfing a preceding smaller black body, which appears during a downtrend. The white body does not necessarily engulf the shadows of the black body but totally engulfs the body itself. This is an important bottom reversal signal.

Recognition Criteria

1. The market is characterized by a prevailing downtrend.
2. A black body is observed on the first day.
3. The white body that is formed on the second day completely engulfs the black body of the preceding day.

(Post 1 of 2) Today's CPI number was expected to be hot, but it actually surprised by coming in even hotter than expected. A "9 handle" on the 9.1% YoY inflation increase was worse than the market expected. However, the initial selloff in the market was cushioned by a bounce that followed.  
 
All 3 major indexes closed off of their lows for the session, albeit they were all still in the red. Bitcoin has traded into the green for most of today. The question we want to consider is, "Why did markets bounce today when the inflation data was so bearish?"  
 
High inflation is bearish for stocks, so why didn't the market sell off sharply, and then stay down? Why did traders step in to buy the dip today? The answer may be that traders believe there is a good chance that we are moving past peak inflation, and that future numbers are likely to be less bearish.

Cryptocurrency lender BlockFi has stopped accepting Grayscale Bitcoin Trust ($GBTC) as collateral and has scaled back from positions related to the investment fund amid contagion spreading from the collapse of hedge fund Three Arrows Capital, Bloomberg reported Tuesday, citing a person with knowledge on the matter. 
 
Both Grayscale, the manager of GBTC, and BlockFi have been exposed to bankrupt Three Arrows. BlockFi has already incurred $80M in losses from 3AC's bad debt, Bloomberg noted, adding that 3AC held 5% of GBTC at one point. 
 
#BlockFi CEO Zac Prince wrote in a Twitter post Monday that his company "directly holds zero GBTC," and "we have small loans (like $10M) w/ GBTC as collateral that are in the process of winding down." 
 
 
The Grayscale Bitcoin Trust's (OTC:GBTC) discount to net asset value keeps rising amid the cyclical slump in bitcoin (BTC-USD). It recently stood at a whopping -31.9%, according to data from YCharts.
